// ch06 scalar table and elsewhere assume ordinary C++ `const`-qualified
// local variables work (e.g. a `const int x = 5;` is unremarkable real
// C++). Currently, `const` is only accepted directly before a reference
// type (`const T&`) or a pointer type (`const T*`) -- a plain `const`
// local variable declaration is rejected ("'const' is only supported
// directly before a reference type ('const T&') or a pointer type
// ('const T*') in this version"). Found while probing whether a closure
// capturing a genuinely `const`-qualified outer variable by reference
// would be treated as a shared (not mutable) reference capture for
// ch05 §5.15's thread-shareable structural derivation -- blocked by this
// more basic gap before that question could even be exercised.
int main() {
    const int x = 5;
    return x;
}
